[src:gson-json-java/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:gson-json-java/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:gson-json-java/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:gson-json-java/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:gson-json-java/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:gson-json-java/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
